stylometry:
RISKSIMTABLE allows you to run several simulations at one time. When we run RISKSIMTABLE in problems it changes the demand input number to a range we have specified in the model. When the simulation is run it will provide the mean, standard deviation, max, minimum, and many other statistical values that you may want to look at. 

For example: There was a problem where we were trying to decide how many rooms to reserve in a hotel based on how many people called ahead and how many people did not and still showed up. We had an input of  a certain number of rooms and then we had several other input numbers varying both up and down from the number given. We up in our decision variable box =RISKSIMTABLE () with the boxes of the values in the (). We ran the simulations by clicking the run simulation button in @RISK. This produces a set of data for us to look at with each of the inputs being what was specified. We then looked at the mean expense, standard deviation of the set and the maximum cost. This allows you to make the best possible decision of how many rooms to order with a low mean cost, low maximum cost, and low standard deviation to minimize the variance of how many people do not show up and use their room.
